I use the term Uberguilds loosly.  By UBERguild, I roll up any guild that has strict requirements to join (Level / Class / FR,CR,MR,PR,DR / etc. etc).  Sure, Afterlife may have been the first (or one of the first) to implement these, but a guild (not just afterlife, but every 'wannabe' guild out there these days) turning away a wonderful human being who is dedicated to this game and improving him/herself to a point that can be effective and helpful to a guild is just rediculous in my eyes.  Again, so people don't misunderstand me later <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   This is a &quot;Generalization&quot; not all Afterlife, Forsaken Realm, XYZ UBERguild members are like this, I have met many to the contrary, it's just the mentality I see as a general on the majority.  I rarely see Afterlife Del, I'm Eurotime and most of the time you are logging on as I'm logging off...but all the guilds that are &quot;fashioning&quot; them selves after your strict recruitment standards.  I just think that a level 23 bard for example, with a willingness to learn and advance himself to help the guild is a much better addition to a guild than a 55 Bard without a personality who only cares about loot.  That's all <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   My summation of my 'opinion' on UBERGuilds and wannabe's.<br>
